recd. yd of 17th cas. I am glad you are well att lille & found yd freives

Lille mr. Richard Souchell
C16 Jun
In antw. ofo yd of 14. cur. I never doubted yd performance in what ym promised
butt you may vere well iudge, that I can not butt take itt un kindely for you
to refuse £100 flemish, which you might dave acceopted the for 22 colliers acctt
domine, & you sad don se for the latter, with all rwason in the would yu
might have redrawne itt, save you accepted for acctt of m collier wishn £40-
of the ballance of is acctt. made up mar last, I have accepted the while
of all accttr, & valeu what de can pretend, & muh more I am engaged for
without any sicuritie, butt the finceritie of dis intentions, I drew on you because
Indanted mony mearly to pay diu bills protested, & I have so muel to pay
withn a month that I tremble to thinck of itt, & I feare, I shall be
obliged to make ise of my creditt, thee by an other trouble is, rat
notwithstanding my complyances m. selliers draws & last post £100- mone
I can nott dilf itt, netha may de blame mee for I shall returne itt
for non acceptance, I can dono more then what I lave den & dover
much wish that every one would use so mucl tindres for mee b
pray selver me Collier the pat sent you
C 16 Juni l682
Duynckircken m Henriy Willinghten
naer dat icq op 11 deser aen ul hebbe ges is den ul van 5d. mij eerst
gewoorden, waer den selven soo lancq deest gedaet is mij onbekent, ul
ordres & dntrest geconsid hebbende, soo hebbe ul rimissa van £200 - van
som de Coninck laeten accep, sal de selve invoorderen & voor ul ord altijt
faraet houden, volgens versoeck daer in anders geen onpbij doen soude
den brief wel weer gesonden hebben, dogh sulckx vont niet geraeden wijt vaeese
dat daer door ul preeud. soude gedaen hebben, te meet odat ul mij geen
contraord. vanden treeken hadde besorght, die andersints daer uyt engon
soude connen maecken tot ul laste, ter wijlen eghter geene preu. geschiet
ende de weerde ul altjt can geremwondenen verwaghte ul antw
Brussel mr. Jrseps Sabbarton
C 16 june 1682
In antwer to yd. of yeasterday, I could wish my bills were payd this week, if I will
beleave them, itt shall be so, though they desired few dayes longer for surplus, god
pray tell them freely that you must ge away, & want the mony, & that I left you
the bills for ready mony, which I hope will make them complye in the meane whis
please to remitt mee no meny thill you recd them, so you can make uso of that
for I could wish you not to draw on mee, saveing al ready disposed of what I
brought wiil mee, I have the packett you sent mee, shall give you credit for
the proved on new acctt & when I recd you packets by thinsday shall send the
acctt of charges to cleare the old. the coppie of vales aggreement is already sent
forward to m colliur, suposeing you sent an other som. Maynard. I fiude
that you saveomitted ap of 27 @ flaine pound lace desired by mine of 2 surt
which I do much want & doven much want itt by the van first, the mee sune
I did then send you, & have no other, so hope that you have itt still, when for send
mee some particular good thing to please avere great freind of mine sn
stalie which exspecting
Brussel Juff. anna Peeters
C 16 dun
hebul brief van gisteren wel ontf. sal heden sonderfant schrijven 't gene juff
almawe heeft versoght, & uijterlijcke devoiren doen om mijne dischage van flanghter
te hebben, & als dan de reste geerne aen ul mamen ter hant stellen, waer van hope
des vol beschayt te weeten. icq ben sondagh over meggelen t'tuys gecomenn alsoo
daer affairens hadde moeste daer passeeren, anders soude tot brussel langer gebleeven
hebben, & ul maner comen besoecken, al toe wel sulckx tot mijn leet wesen doen om
dierwille dat bij daer niet als droesheyt bevinde, & icq, daer niet telpen on
t gene noghtans wenschte doen conde, soo getis voorders van Eng. verneme sal ul laeten
weeten
ondon m. Henry Maynard
C 17 June 1682
mij last to you was on the 10 surds sence saveing been att Brussel is the reesen that
I have not sooner answered yd of 26 & 29 past, & 2 cur, John vale dave composed att 40
as mr. Sabbaeton will advise you, & more particolarly when be shall be wish you
I have given you credit for the pack of spanish cloaches loaden aboard klerck, I could
with you gad shipped one aboard ranlarson which came sence from londen, what
spanish cloathes you buy lett them be good, or rather non. I have also given you credit
for my ½ in the kersies from the north, which pray endeavour to gett aboard of smisl
for I shall want thom & ben first, tassen also the G.W. silver marex, & the stamelds
butt I could wish you gott more then one att least 2 or 3 yett send mee forward what
att is, & as soone as you receave any as for the northren trade I finde m. Hill
doth best of any you dave bethert imployed, so that you micht aggree with him
I have had goods from fanm. tijken, which indeed weer vere good, butt est seems he
leaves all to de mett now, haveing to much bistijnes, so that I do not knw what to
advise you, butt whese you be there, you will be able to iudge more thin I cando
white Joseph vivian lived, & whent in to the norch he found Rot hipping, which sended
the best goods that ever I had, yett sndeed I sad never any yet, that can be compared
